<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%>
	   <a name=104165735673452></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f104165735673452><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=104165735673452>RE: Armor Stats</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=104165735673452#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=200639><span id= >Ronney</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Jan 4th 12:42 AM 2003</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>With 1500 pp on a new bard your best bet is a fairly full set of Validus Custodus plate (100 - 200 pp a piece - but drops in Kael I think if u want to collect it with your main) with a Carnelian ring or two (to counter the plate neg AGI stats).&nbsp;&nbsp;If your AGI is high enough with just one ring then pick up a Silver Jacinth ring (10 ac) or a Jagged Band (5 ac 3 STR) for your other finger.  VC plate gives LOTS of STR, some HP, and very decent AC on all bits. Ignore STA on items, instead placing start points into it (and STR) - STA is important - but nothing that JJV cant fix (CHA is EASY to get to high levels with items if needed - arguably a poor choice to put (m)any points into this).<br><br>Other stats are *pointless* until higher levels, and I would argue DEX is always a wasted stat on a bard (so long as its not too low!).  Why? Well, at low levels your primary damage output will be through melee and high ac and str will help you lvl far quicker.  CHA is unnecessary until SBB (KLL is too unreliable to be useful), and even then you'll usually be far better off fear-kiting (mobs around 30 dont have too many hitpoints for a solo bard to melee away quickly - add 10 levels and this changes though, not to mention the pounding u'll take when that nice Ravishing Drovlarg decides to resist your fear).  DEX may mean a few fewer missed notes, but as already said, primary damage output will be from melee at lower levels. When soloing later on you wont tend to get hit (some form of kiting is *required*), and if you happen to be grouped then it is your job not to grab the agro from the tank (yes, its more your job, not his to taunt it off you!) ... and if you're not being hit then missed notes shouldnt be a problem. Thus DEX is wasteful.<br><br>INT (or +mana)is important later on - no, not to waste it on DDDirge but rather on SD charm ... bards are highly sought after in groups for crowd control, indeed on occasion more so than chanters unless big trains (by big I'm thinking Cazic-style, not Karnor's) are expected (they are a more flexible class, and can also take far more punishment from enraged mobs after broken charm/mez =&gt; easier on clerics mana in a train situation).<br><br>So ... I'd get AC/HP/STR for lower levels, and phase these items out with CHA / higher HP+AC / INT items later on (in that order of priority) when you start to be called on for crowd control duties or want to charm kite (though triple-chant is generally more useful for xp killing due to limited mana, especially from 49 with the long lasting selos).  MR is always handy too at higher lvls - bards do a lot of pulling, but a rooted bard is a dead one :) =&gt; resists on already good items are a bonus.<br><br>As a final word, if you want a good bard weapon that will last right up to high levels then try to pick up a Crystalline Short Sword for a low price ... very decent bardish stats, good output, and no proc (this is a consideration for higher lvls - in groups you'll increase agro with one - and that's yet another reason why DEX is not overly important to a bard).<br><br>Ronney Marmalade &lt;Nexus of Dreams&gt;<br>Antonius Bayle<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Sat Jan  4 00:34:40 2003</em><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>

