	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103828610412847><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=4&mid=103828610412847>RE: Newbie Armour for a Vah Shir bard</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4&mid=103828610412847#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=189041><span id=Scholar>Ratguy</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>26 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Nov 26th 12:11 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.60]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Thanx for the advice.&nbsp;&nbsp;I had actually gotten out of Shar Val by my 3rd level and went to North Qeynos to kill rats.  Large Rats and Giant Rats drop Plague rat tails (more regularly than plague rats do actually) which sell to vendors for about 1pp 5gp and change.  Not bad money at level 1-5.  The ones around the gnome city (Ak'Anon I think) drop the plague rat tails more frequently, but the stores can be a problem to fit into with larger races. Faction in the qeynos area is easy to raise too.  Just kill gnoll pups.  The benefit of these is that you get faction, and bags for carrying loot until you can afford better.  Also, as you move onto higher level gnolls collect the no drop teeth and hand them into the Gaurd Captain above the arena in SQ as this will give you exp, gold and faction (remember to give some to the woman in the pit in Halas if you intend to hunt mamoths at some stage too as this increases faction, gives you food and torches).  I find this a better way of making money as I don't have to rely on the off chance of a smith being on when I am.  I play early morning US time but will keep the farming idea in mind.  Might try and get a ranger to go to WK and farm there since the same stuff is available and they require the spiderling silk for their newbie armour quest.  The silk can be made into bandages too which will raise tailoring close to 30 from memory.<br><br>Now for a digression, if my previous rambling weren't already:)<br><br>I find it interesting that you believe HP the most important stat for everyone.  I know with my ranger I find the most important thing is not to get hit (don't get hit and you don't need HP, that's what tanks are for), which can be difficult when you're normally the one doing the pulling so getting agro first.  Rangers also have roughly the same HP as Bards/clerics lower AC and worse defencive skills than a bard does after level 50 (same cap of 200 until then), so when they do get hit it is for more damage.  So for a ranger agro management is the most important thing (the person behind the keyboard knowing what they are doing in other words), agi so that you don't get hit (improves dodging and increases AC), sta (duration of fighting, length of time holding breath and extra HP), str (for dealing more damage with each hit, less time the thing is alive the less chance of getting hit) and Wisdom (for casting of spells and fletching, the never ending quest for better arrows).<br><br>Putting this type of information into a bard, I had come up with the following.  Sta (for HP, breath duration and long melee abilities if required, also clears up sta regen songs for something more useful like a DoT or heal), agi is replaced by dex (better ability to play instruments which is after all the bards trade). Wis is not important at all for a bard that I can see so this is replaced by Cha (helps with charm/fear songs).  Str may also be of use as it helps with carrying all that nice high AC armour around but this is easy to increase with things like earrings and rings.<br><br>Of course I could be barking up the wrong tree here but it has worked well for me with the ranger.  I have only hunted with 2 bards since I started playing the game and while I thought neither character was played very well (one of the bards kept running out of song effect range even when they weren't drawing any agro and the other just refused to play music during combat), I could see some great potential in what a well played bard could do, and it did look like an interesting character type to play.  Still, any advice is always welcome, especially from those that have been playing the class longer than me.<br><br>Just a footnote to this.  Just got off from hunting with a bard that seemed to know their job and talk about making life easier for us all:)  Mezz, slow, DoT's, group heal and mana regen took the edge off most fights and made down time almost non-existant.  Must say that it was a pleasure.  I was playing my ranger as a tank, which was only achievable thanx to the bards skill, and not something anyone should expect rangers to do.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Nov 26 07:00:57 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>40 season Half Elf Ranger <br>8 song Var Shir Bard <br>level 6 gnome wizard<br>Kayne Bayle Server</td></tr>
